ce:section.ce:para:
The unit cell of a cellulose chain with six C6H10O5 units was constructed. The GQD is attached to the cellulose chain via the carboxyl groups to build the structure of the cellulose–GQD nanocomposite (Fig. 1
                     ), according to the experimental data [33,34] and theoretical study [35,36]. Periodicity along the cellulose chain was assumed with aperiodicity along the other two perpendicular directions to avoid self-interaction. The edge of the GQD was covered with a variety of functional groups, namely amino (NH2), methyl (CH3), aldehyde (CHO), ketone (COCH3), nitro (NO2), hydroxyl (OH), and carboxyl (COOH) (Fig. 2
                     ). These functional groups have been shown to be experimentally abundant in the GQDs [37–39], except for CH3, which was used for comparison.

Fig. 4
 shows that the energy levels of HOMOs and LUMOs of GQD-OH@cellulose, GQD-NH2@cellulose, and GQD-CH3@cellulose shift to more positive values compared to cellulose–GQD, whereas the energy levels of HOMOs and LUMOs of GQD-COOH@cellulose, GQD-COCH3@cellulose, GQD-NO2@cellulose, and GQD-CHO @cellulose shift to more negative values than those of cellulose–GQD. This trend of energy shift agrees with the previous study [61]. However, the band gap of cellulose–GQD nanocomposites attached by a functional group containing a CO double bond increases compared to the non-functionalized cellulose–GQD nanocomposite, while the band gap of nanocomposites attached by a functional group without a CO double bond decreases. The analysis of the charge transfer from the GQD to the cellulose chain and the functional group (Fig. 5

) shows that the charge transfer in the cellulose–GQD nanocomposite with a CO double bond is higher than in the cellulose–GQD nanocomposite without a CO double bond. The more charge transferred from the GQD to the cellulose chain, the lower the screening, which leads to a larger quasiparticle correction of the GQD and thus to a larger band gap [61]. The trend of charge transfer in cellulose–GQD nanocomposites is GQD-NO2@cellulose > GQD-CHO@cellulose > GQD-COCH3@cellulose > GQD-COOH@cellulose > GQD-CH3@cellulose > GQD-NH2@cellulose > GQD-OH@cellulose and is different from its GQD counterparts (GQD-NH2 > GQD-OH > GQD-COOH > GQD-CHO > GQD-COCH3 > GQD-CH3) [61], suggesting that the GQD-cellulose interaction has a significant impact on the electronic structure of the GQD.
